I disagree. I think it gives us a very useful, albeit very limited, amount of insight into the Doctor himself. He obviously cared for this creature, so much so that he apparently sent it to the Circus for two reason: One, he knew it would be a place he could entertain people, make them happy. Two, he seems to have known the Foundation would find out eventualy, and that they would take care of him. It seems almost like Wondertainment looks at him like a son he isn't capable of taking care of, something that pains him. Which is why he doesn't want to hear about it anymore. It brings him that much grief. It humanizes Wondertainment, shows that he -really does- want to help people, even his creations, and that he holds *no* ill-will towards the Foundation, and views them as the second-best option for his inevitable failures, something I feel haunts him every day of his life.







